caption:
How come we never get IMAX movies at home? 

If you load up Tron: Ares right now on Disney+, you’re going to see something called IMAX Enhanced. Now, this is kind of a gimmick, and I’m going to tell you why. Tron Aries was actually shot for a 2.39 widescreen aspect ratio, but cinematographer Jeff Cronenworth protected the 1.90 for IMAX screens in movie theaters. Because in a real movie theater, when you’re in a physical space, that expanded aspect ratio in IMAX is amazing. But that expanded aspect ratio at home on your TV essentially means nothing. You’re just getting a few more pixels. It doesn’t change the story. You’re not getting information that you may have missed if you didn’t see it in IMAX. It’s just a little bit bigger. But people love to complain that we’re not getting proper IMAX releases at home, and I have a hot take on this. I don’t think we should. Not even Christopher Nolan has ever released a true 1.43 IMAX expanded ratio at home. You need to trust that these filmmakers are giving you the optimal best viewing experience that they think is right for their movie on the screen that you’re watching it on. Because like I said at the beginning, IMAX is not just an expanded aspect ratio. It’s an experience. It’s about being in an actual space, looking at a giant movie screen, and going, holy shit. And that is an experience. You will never be able to replicate at home. I don’t care how big your TV is. So I say keep IMAX special. Keep that expanded ratio for the cinema. And if you want to experience true IMAX films, get your ass to a movie theater.

#movies #imax #tron

caption:
If Netflix movies look so bad… why does this one look so good?

WAKE UP DEAD MAN is easily one of the best looking films of the year. Aesthetically, it feels like the anti-streaming movie… streaming movie. Nearly everything people complain about these days like flat lighting, boring blocking, and bland, muddy imagery is nonexistent here. Everything about this film is so well crafted and beautiful, which might make some of you wonder… how is this a Netflix movie?

There’s a consensus lately that Netflix, and even all the other streamers, are part of some bad cinematography illuminati. Like every ugly movie isn’t the fault of who made it, it’s the app you use to watch it. This is nonsense.

Rian Johnson and his cinematographer Steve Yedlin shot the hell out of this film. They didn’t cut a single corner. They intentionally created sets and spaces to frame and light like artists, and that’s why this movie looks incredible. It was made by talented people.

And I know some of you will argue, well, WAKE UP DEAD MAN was like a $200 million movie. They could do whatever they wanted. But here’s another Netflix movie that cost over $200 million… and it doesn’t look like this. So it’s not resources.

We need to have a serious conversation about taste. Because Netflix has proven time and time again that they do have good taste. They just recently acquired TRAIN DREAMS to stream as a Netflix original, and that’s another absolutely gorgeous film. But the number of people with great taste, and the ability to consistently create great films, is very small. The number of people with mediocre taste who can pump out a high volume of content is huge.

WAKE UP DEAD MAN proves the problem isn’t Netflix. It’s us. All of us constantly want new things. We are never satisfied. We say we want craft, then we binge slop, then complain everything looks like shit.

These studios and companies are giving us exactly what we’ve shown them we’ll accept. Speed over care. Volume over intention. Familiar over new.

If you want movies like this, stop demanding more. Start demanding better. Because taste can’t be mass-produced. It has to be curated.

#movies #film #cinema

caption:
It’s Marty’s world and we’re just living in it. 

The cinematography in this movie is unbelievable, and I’m going to tell you why. Marty Supreme is a truly gorgeous-looking film, but when we talk about good cinematography, we tend to only focus on the camera, lenses, and lighting. But there’s two more crucial components to a great-looking image, and that’s spaces and faces. Director Josh Safdie hired Jack Fisk to create the world of Marty Supreme, and Jack is one of the most legendary production designers in the world. He’s worked with Terrence Malick, Paul Thomas Anderson, and Martin Scorsese. Jack made sure that the world of this movie felt real by recreating 1950s New York and Tokyo with real practical sets. And what’s so crazy is that so much of this film is shot on long lenses, meaning all you really see is the close-up of a character’s face. And I asked Jack what it was like to build sets that only show up for a brief moment. Now, because so much of this film is filled with faces, I think what makes Josh such a brilliant director is his ability to cast supporting roles with non-traditional Hollywood actors. The human face tells its own story. And when you see characters in this movie, you can see their backstory. You can feel it. And when you combine all the incredible spaces that Jack built with all of these interesting faces, and then you get Darius Khondji, one of the greatest cinematographers in the world, to light it and shoot it, that’s how you end up with Marty Supreme, the type of movie that reminds you why you love movies.

caption:
Stop watching movies wrong. 

Everyone I know, my friends and family, every time they book tickets to a movie, they’re finding seats that are close to the back. It might seem counterintuitive, but when you sit further back, the screen actually gets smaller. James Cameron, aka Papa Jim, just put out a really great video explaining where you should sit in the auditorium for Avatar: Fire and Ash. I love this video because what he explains is something I’ve been trying to tell people forever: sit close to the screen. Especially with a movie like Avatar: Fire and Ash, in IMAX, you want that screen to envelop your entire peripheral vision, meaning all that you see is screen. You have to look left and right to see the entire image. I can prove this to you because I watched Avatar: Fire and Ash, second row center in 3D on one of the largest IMAX screens in the world, and I thought I was gonna die. Like, no hyperbole, there’s a moment in this thing where you’re dipping in and out of, like, these river rapids underwater, and I instinctively jumped out of my seat. Like, I came forward ‘cause I thought I had to gasp for air underwater. Do you understand how insane that is? I’ve been going to the cinema for the better part of 30 years and I’ve never had this feeling before where I actually was fearful for my own safety. I’m starting to realize I might be turning you off sitting in the front row, but I’m telling you, these are the cinematic experiences that you remember for the rest of your life. Obviously, you don’t have to sit in the actual front row. Jim actually suggests sitting in those first, like, 10, 15 rows. I think the first five, six rows are the perfect spot to be. Right the hell there. And the best part is, the cool people sit up front. All the losers that are on their phone and they’re talking, they’re always in the back. Avatar: Fire and Ash is a movie unlike anything I’ve ever seen before. It honestly feels like a drug and if you really want a high dose of this drug, sit in the front row.

#movies #imax #cinema

Depth in 3D movies come from the horizontal disparity between the two images, and sitting in the front row introduces distortion and vertical disparity that can compress/warp the depth (something IMAX front row is FAMOUS for) because of how off axis you are. That’s why centered viewing positions are recommended, including by Jim Cameron, in your reel. If you’re arguing that IMAX avoids this, I’d be interested in hearing that argument.
